[0m[49m[39m  274, 264[0m:[39m[49m The anomaly detection framing requires a per-patient baseline. This is where the problem gets interesting, because baselines in healthcare are never as simple as "the patient's average."
[0m[49m[39m  275, 265[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  276, 266[0m:[39m[49m A naive baseline is the patient's lifetime no-show rate: `prior_no_shows / prior_completed_or_no_show_appointments`. Simple. Interpretable. Leaks in several ways:
[0m[49m[39m  277, 267[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 278     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m - **Cold start.** New patients have no history. What's their baseline? You can't call it zero (which would imply they always show). You can't call it the population mean (which might not apply). The standard fix is Bayesian smoothing: start with a prior distribution based on cohort features and update toward the patient's observed rate as you accumulate observations. A Beta distribution with a population-derived prior is the usual tool; you get a baseline for every patient including brand-new ones, and it converges to the patient-specific rate as history accumulates.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      268[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Cold start.** New patients have no history. What's their baseline? You can't call it zero (which would imply they always show). You can't call it the population mean (which might not apply). The standard fix is Bayesian smoothing: start with a prior distribution based on cohort features and update toward the patient's observed rate as you accumulate observations. A Beta distribution with a population-derived prior is the usual tool; you get a baseline for every patient including brand-new ones, and it converges to the patient-specific rate as history accumulates. In practice, you pick a population-level prior (say the system-wide no-show rate is 0.18) and express it as a Beta distribution with an effective sample size of about 10: `Beta(alpha_prior=1.8, beta_prior=8.2)`. That means a brand-new patient starts with a baseline of 0.18 and each real observation pulls the posterior toward the patient's true rate. After about 8 observations (`MIN_BASELINE_OBSERVATIONS = 8`), the posterior is dominated by the patient's own data rather than the prior. For high-frequency specialties like dialysis or oncology, that's a few months. For routine primary care with annual visits, that's several years, which is why the prior matters so much: you'll be relying on it for a long time for many patients.
