[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      316[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The same selection-bias discipline applies to the patient baseline updates. If you intervene on a high-risk patient and they show up (because you called them), their no-show rate was artificially suppressed by the intervention. If you feed that suppressed outcome back into their baseline, the patient's rolling rate drifts downward toward the intervention-adjusted rate over months of operation. The deviation calculation that is the core of the anomaly signal degrades: eventually all your successfully-intervened high-risk patients look "normal" and the investigation queue stops surfacing useful contextual anomalies. The fix is simple: only update the patient baseline when no intervention was applied to that appointment. Track an `intervened_observation_count` separately so you can audit how many data points were excluded and whether the exclusion is materially changing the baseline trajectory. The training pipeline already does this exclusion (the `intervention_count = 0` filter in the retrain query); the baseline update must do the same.
