[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 988     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m specialty disclosure: for behavioral health, addiction medicine, OB/GYN, infectious
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 989     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m disease, and oncology clinics, the clinic name itself is a diagnostic disclosure. SMS
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 990     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m messages are visible on lock screens, on shared family-plan devices, and in carrier
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 991     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m billing logs. The minimum-necessary message body for those specialties is typically time
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 992     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m plus a generic identifier; the clinic or specialty name should only be included when the
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 993     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m patient has explicitly opted into specialty-disclosing reminders. Recommend a per-clinic
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 994     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m "reminder content sensitivity" flag in the patient-preference store with template
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 995     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m selection gated on it. -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      987[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **High-stigma specialty disclosure.** For behavioral health, addiction medicine, OB/GYN, infectious disease/sexual health, and oncology clinics, the clinic name itself is a diagnostic disclosure. SMS messages traverse carrier networks, are visible on lock screens, show in shared family-plan billing logs, and can appear in notification previews on linked devices. The minimum-necessary message body for these specialties is typically the appointment time plus a generic identifier ("your healthcare appointment"), with no clinic or specialty name unless the patient has explicitly opted into specialty-disclosing reminders. Implement a per-clinic `reminder_content_sensitivity` flag in the patient-preference store; gate message-template selection on it. Clinics flagged as high-sensitivity get a generic template by default, and patients who want specifics can opt in through the portal. This is the same minimum-necessary pattern flagged in Recipes 2.7-2.10 and 3.1, applied to the patient-facing message surface.
