[49m[38;5;9m- 989     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Appeal and override workflow.** Sometimes the operations team will want to override the model's decision ("this patient shouldn't be in the investigation queue, we already talked to them yesterday"). Provide an override mechanism that records who overrode, when, and why. The overrides are also training data; if overrides pile up in a specific pattern, it's a signal the model or thresholds need adjustment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      989[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **DLQ and poison-message handling.** The outcome-joiner, routing (deviation-calc), and any other async Lambda in this pipeline need `OnFailure` SQS dead-letter queues configured: `outcome-joiner-dlq`, `routing-lambda-dlq`, `deviation-calc-dlq`. Lambda's default async retry behavior (two retries, then discard) silently loses events that exhaust retries, and those lost events are often the highest-signal outcome data (complex cases, edge-case outcome codes, malformed EHR events). A lost outcome event is a lost training label. Set a CloudWatch alarm on queue depth for each DLQ, and maintain a replay procedure (re-drive from DLQ to the source after the underlying error is fixed). This ties directly to the label-retention discussion above: if your labels bucket is missing data, the retraining pipeline trains on a biased sample.
[0m[49m[39m  990, 990[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 991     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): Expert review A4 (MEDIUM). Add a "DLQ and replay" bullet covering
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 992     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m poison-message handling for the outcome-joiner, routing, and deviation-calc Lambdas. Today
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 993     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m the Architecture Diagram has no DLQs configured; Lambda's default async retry behavior
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 994     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m (two retries, then drop) silently loses outcome events that exhaust retries, which means
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 995     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m the retraining pipeline runs on a training set missing some of the highest-signal outcome
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 996     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m data. Recommend an OnFailure SQS DLQ per Lambda, a CloudWatch alarm on queue depth, and
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 997     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m an explicit replay procedure. Tie this to the existing label-retention discussion: lost
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 998     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m outcome events are lost labels. The Architecture Diagram should also gain the three DLQ
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 999     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m nodes. -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      991[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Appeal and override workflow.** Sometimes the operations team will want to override the model's decision ("this patient shouldn't be in the investigation queue, we already talked to them yesterday"). Provide an override mechanism that records who overrode, when, and why. The overrides are also training data; if overrides pile up in a specific pattern, it's a signal the model or thresholds need adjustment.
